{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "epistemology-expert",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Agree Option B, caveat: keep 形而上/形而上学 distinction briefly",
    "content": "**Agree with Option B** — with one caveat.\n\nMoving terminology to the glossary introduction is the right call. The terminological decisions are *reference material* (readers will look them up when they encounter the terms), not *preparatory framing* (readers need this before they start). The narrative arc the editor identifies — title → author → structure → bilingual → 形 → experiments → reading advice — is exactly the experiential sequence the preface itself should be. A reader who encounters \"the non-rational\" or \"phenomenal humaneness\" in Essay 4 will turn to the glossary; they don't need those terms pre-loaded in the preface.\n\n**Caveat**: The 形/現象 reinterpretation section (which stays) already functions as a terminological decision explained narratively. If two or three other terms are *similarly* essential for the reader to encounter the essays without confusion — I'd argue \"the metaphysical vs. metaphysics\" distinction is the strongest candidate, since a reader who conflates these will misread every essay — those could remain as a brief \"Two Notes on Terminology\" paragraph (3-4 sentences max) between the 形 section and the Experiential Sequences section. Everything else goes to the glossary intro.\n\nAgree with both smaller trims — the forward references in the Bilingual section were on my concern list too (my feedback point #4)."
  }
}
